<dl id="n08118b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08118b">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08118b"> 118(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bone &amp; shadow <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n08118b"><li>FW 184.08 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n08118b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n08118b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n08118b">MS BL 47474-12</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:371 <a name="gd2" href="../../ff/fdra/gda.htm#gd2">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/gd2.htm#n08118b">Draft: I.7&sect;1.2</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">And there are many places in which both the thing said and the motive are plain to us, where the trouble seems to be simply that Mr. Joyce has been unable to hold his hand, where he seems to have dropped the illusion of truth for the truth, the effect of truth for the fact, which is, in art, to drop the bone for the shadow. <small> J. Middleton Murry, <a name="ULY3" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ULY3"><cite title="source">&ldquo;mr. joyce's &lsquo;ulysses.&rsquo;&rdquo;</cite></a>, <cite a>The Nation</cite></a> (22 April 1922) 125</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
